:"1387–Overleden","1371–Female":"1371–Overleden","1338":"1338","1457":"1457","about 1338":"circa 1338","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1371":"1371","1409":"1409","about 1364":"circa 1364","of,Dinmael cmt,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Glyntarell,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1338–":"about 1338–Deceased","1338–Male":"1338–Deceased","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1409–1457":"1409–1457","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","1364–Female":"1364–Deceased","1387–Male":"1387–Deceased","1371–Female":"1371–Deceased","1338":"1338","1457":"1457","about 1338":"about 1338","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1371":"1371","1409":"1409","about 1364":"about 1364","of,Dinmael cmt,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Glyntarell,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]},{"name":"Fychan\"","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ieuan \" Fychan\" ap Ieuan was born about 1338, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Madog Fychan William Hywel, was -47 and his mother, Gwenhwyfar ferch Ieuan, was -31. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. Ieuan Fychan ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1338–":"umbes 1338–Surnud","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1409–1457":"1409–1457","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1342–Female":"1342–Surnud","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1371–Female":"1371–Surnud","1338":"1338","1457":"1457","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1371":"1371","1409":"1409","about 1364":"umbes 1364","of,Dinmael cmt,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Glyntarell,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1338–":"noin 1338–Kuollut","1338–Male":"1338–Kuollut","1395–Male":"1395–Kuol